Title

Space DMV: A Civilian-Centered Coordination Layer for Ground, Air, and Orbital Mobility

Abstract

Space DMV is a non-governmental, civilian-first coordination platform designed to bridge ground, air, and emerging space mobility systems. It does not replace state DMVs or federal aviation authorities; instead, it provides a unified operator experience and a safe interoperability layer for hybrid and future vehicles that cross traditional jurisdictional boundaries.

The system is built around three pillars:

• Federated identity (DMV‑O, FAAO, Space‑O)
• Digital Vessel Verification (DVV) for hybrid and space-capable craft
• Safety Protocol Chain (SPC‑1.0) focused on emotional, physical, and operational safety


Space DMV is intentionally local-first, privacy-preserving, and non-regulatory. It is designed to be adopted voluntarily by agencies and operators as mobility systems evolve.

---

1. Problem Space

Modern mobility is fragmenting:

• State DMVs govern ground vehicles.
• FAA (and equivalents) govern airspace and aircraft.
• No widely adopted framework exists for hybrid ground–air–space vehicles, orbital shuttles, or civilian space mobility.


This creates gaps in:

• Operator experience (multiple disjoint systems)
• Safety protocols across domains
• Identity continuity (one human, many roles)
• Future readiness for hybrid vehicles and small craft


Space DMV addresses these gaps without claiming regulatory authority.

---

2. Design Principles

1. Sovereignty Respect• State DMVs remain authoritative for ground vehicles.
• FAA remains authoritative for airspace and aircraft.
• Space DMV never issues legal licenses or certifications.

2. Federated Identity, Not Centralization• Operators authenticate via DMV‑O, FAAO, or Space‑O.
• Space DMV consumes tokens, it does not own legal identity.

3. Read-Only Interoperability• Space DMV can verify DMV/FAA data via APIs.
• It does not write to or modify government systems.

4. Operator Dignity & Emotional Safety• Interfaces are calm, non-punitive, and non-violent.
• Safety protocols include emotional and sensory considerations.

5. Local-First & Privacy-Preserving• Prototypes can run entirely in-browser.
• No data leaves the device unless explicitly configured.



---

3. Core Components

3.1 Unified Login Portal (ULP‑1.0)

A neutral front-end that allows operators to log in using:

• DMV‑O (state DMV identity provider)
• FAAO (FAA identity provider)
• Space‑O (Space DMV identity provider)


The ULP uses standard protocols (e.g., OAuth/OIDC) and does not store identity data. It simply assembles an Identity Envelope (IE‑1.0).

3.2 Identity Envelope (IE‑1.0)

A logical container that includes:

• Legal name (from DMV‑O)
• State ID token
• Pilot certificate token (if present)
• Space operator token (if present)
• Safety profile (gravity comfort, access needs, non-violent pledge)
• Mission context (what the operator is doing in this session)


The Identity Envelope is used internally by Space DMV to determine what flows and safety protocols apply.

---

3.3 Space DMV Core Platform (SDCP‑1.0)

Key modules:

• Operator Console
UI for operators to manage missions, vessels, and training.
• DVV Registry
Digital Vessel Verification for hybrid and space-capable craft.
DVV is analogous to a VIN, but extended for multi-domain vehicles.
• Safety Protocol Engine (SPC‑1.0)
Encodes non-violent navigation, emergency calm procedures, gravity and access matching, and other safety logic.
• Training & Simulation Layer
Scenario-based training for hybrid vehicles, orbital operations, and emergency handling.
• API Gateway
Manages read-only, opt-in integrations with DMV and FAA systems.


---

4. Three-Lane Mobility Model

Space DMV assumes three primary mobility domains:

1. Ground (DMV)• Cars, motorcycles, ground hybrids, autonomous pods.

2. Air (FAA)• Drones, helicopters, small aircraft, eVTOL, air hybrids.

3. Space (Space DMV)• Suborbital craft, orbital shuttles, hybrid ground–air–space vehicles, training simulators, research and family shuttles.



Space DMV focuses on Lane 3 and the bridges between lanes, especially for hybrid vehicles that transition between ground, air, and space.

---

5. DVV: Digital Vessel Verification

DVV is a structured identity for vessels that may operate across multiple domains.

A DVV record may include:

• Vessel name and class
• Hybrid capabilities (ground/air/space)
• Safety rating and certification status
• Owner/operator linkage
• Maintenance and inspection logs
• Mission history (non-invasive, high-level)
• Emergency profile (abort modes, safe landing options)


DMV and FAA can verify DVV records via read-only APIs, but cannot modify them. Space DMV can use DVV to determine which safety protocols and training flows are required.

---

6. Safety Protocol Chain (SPC‑1.0)

SPC‑1.0 is a layered safety model that activates based on:

• Operator identity and experience
• Vessel class and capabilities
• Mission type and risk level
• Operator’s stated comfort and access needs


It includes:

• Non-violent navigation pledge
• Emergency calm protocol (stepwise, non-panicked guidance)
• Gravity comfort matching (avoid harmful environments)
• Access needs accommodation (sensory, cognitive, physical)
• Hybrid transition safety (ground ↔ air ↔ space)
• Abort and return logic
• Kid-safe participation modes


The goal is to reduce cognitive and emotional load, not increase it.

---

7. Governance & Adoption

Space DMV is designed to be:

• Adoptable by agencies as a coordination tool
• Optional for operators and states
• Transparent in its data handling
• Non-regulatory by default


It can be piloted as:

• A training and simulation platform
• A research tool for hybrid mobility
• A public education interface
• A ceremonial “future DMV” prototype


